Are Ideas Getting Harder to Find?=C2=A0
I spent the weekend at Progress Conference 2024 [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/97fdf814-8d58-4deb-acfe-abb3d914d50a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], hosted by Jason Crawford, Heike Larson=
, and the team at the Roots of Progress Institute. It was awesome. A group =
of my favorite progress thinkers and doers from the internet came to Lighth=
aven in Berkeley to discuss the question: how do we make more progress?=C2=
=A0
There was a range of talks and topics, but the topic that came up the most =
was some version of a debate over the 2020 paper by Nicholas Bloom, Chad Jo=
nes, John Van Reenen, and Michael Webb, Are Ideas Getting Harder to Find [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/e9f9d802-ba21-4cd5-9e7f-4ce39329653a?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]?
If ideas are getting harder to find and if the =E2=80=9Clow hanging fruit h=
as been picked=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 and the authors argue that they are and i=
t has =E2=80=93 then it=E2=80=99s unsurprising that we are stagnating.=C2=
=A0
Economic growth, they write, is a function of ideas, which is a function of=
 research productivity and number of researchers.=C2=A0
To determine whether new ideas had indeed become harder to find, they looke=
d at three specific case studies =E2=80=93 Moore=E2=80=99s Law, seed yields=
, and medical innovations =E2=80=93 and at the growth of the economy as a w=
hole.=C2=A0
They found that in all the cases they examined, it=E2=80=99s taken more res=
earchers just to find the same number of ideas over time, which means that =
ideas are getting harder to find, which implies that we either need to thro=
w an exponentially increasing number of researchers at problems just to mai=
ntain our current growth rate (maybe possible with AI!) or settle in for a =
long stagnation.=C2=A0
I am not an economist, so maybe this is just how these things work, but the=
 whole argument strikes me as incredibly circular:=C2=A0
The paper defines ideas as things that lead to Total Factor Productivity (T=
FP) growth.
TFP is the portion of economic output growth that cannot be explained by in=
creases in the quantity of inputs (like labor and capital).=C2=A0
The paper then measures research productivity as TFP growth divided by rese=
arch input.
Finally, it concludes that because this ratio is declining, ideas are getti=
ng harder to find.
By defining ideas in terms of TFP growth, the paper essentially assumes its=
 conclusion.=C2=A0
The paper does provide valuable data on the relationship between research i=
nputs and certain economic outputs over time, and it finds this pattern acr=
oss various domains, which suggests there's something meaningful happening.=
 And the authors have forgotten more about economics than I=E2=80=99ll ever=
 learn, so maybe I=E2=80=99m missing something.=C2=A0
The problem is, the paper might actually lead to the wrong conclusion: that=
 we need to throw more researchers at the problem, that we just need to pro=
duce more ideas.=C2=A0
For one thing, it might suggest that now that AI is here, we=E2=80=99re goo=
d. While the number of human researchers won=E2=80=99t be able to scale exp=
onentially to offset declining research productivity, maybe the number of A=
I researchers can. If you assume that ideas are the bottleneck, then maybe =
you just hold out for a sufficiently intelligent model.=C2=A0
The question of whether AI would just solve progress came up multiple times=
 at the conference.=C2=A0
The most common response was: no, ideas are not the bottleneck.=C2=A0
On the opposite end of the spectrum, it might suggest that we are really an=
d truly screwed. Total Factor Productivity really has fallen off since the =
1970s, and if ideas just keep getting harder to find, and ideas are what dr=
ive TFP, then we might just be in for greater and greater stagnation.
Both of these are dangerous but passive. Wait and see.=C2=A0
A third option, implied but not recommended by the paper, would be to throw=
 more at research: more people, more education, more money. If ideas are ge=
tting harder to find =E2=80=93 if it takes more =E2=80=9Ceffective research=
ers=E2=80=9D to generate the same number of ideas =E2=80=93 then we need to=
 produce more researchers to at least match the rate of decline in research=
 productivity.=C2=A0
That strikes me as equivalent to observing that a football team=E2=80=99s y=
ards per carry is declining and deciding that they need to run the ball mor=
e to make up for it. To torture this analogy a bit, it=E2=80=99s maybe even=
 more equivalent to signing more running backs, whoever=E2=80=99s available=
 off waivers, and then running the ball more with them, instead of fixing y=
our offensive line. Worse, there are only 53 roster spots, so every new run=
ning back you sign means cutting someone who could be doing the blocking an=
d tackling!
We will always need new ideas. In this house, we subscribe to the David Deu=
tsch Principle of Optimism [ https://substack.com/redirect/23607a4c-3340-4d=
93-a274-28785b743ef6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: =E2=80=9CAll evils are caused by insufficient knowledge.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0
And to be fair, the paper isn=E2=80=99t trying to suggest that a lack of id=
eas is solely responsible for the slowdown in TFP growth. It=E2=80=99s simp=
ly arguing that the assumption of constant research productivity doesn=E2=
=80=99t hold up, and it makes its point.=C2=A0
But the simplistic takeaways =E2=80=93 that ideas are getting harder to com=
e by so either we=E2=80=99re doomed, can expect AI to save us, or need to t=
hrow more researchers at the problem =E2=80=93 are dangerous and, I think, =
wrong.=C2=A0
There are plenty of good ideas waiting to be turned into progress. There=E2=
=80=99s an idea backlog.=C2=A0
The Idea Backlog
So why are so many companies being built today using ideas from the 1950s a=
nd 1960s?=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s look at this chart again:=C2=A0
One thing that the paper omits is any discussion of why, if research produc=
tivity had been declining fairly steadily and the number of effective resea=
rchers had been rising fairly steadily since the 1930s, there was such a dr=
amatic fall-off in TFP starting in 1973.=C2=A0
That is a major omission! If the slowdown in TFP growth can be explained by=
 ideas getting harder to find, why did growth hit a brick wall in 1973 as o=
pposed to slowly decaying as soon as ideas became harder to find?=C2=A0
Well, one question to ask might be =E2=80=9CWhich factors contributed to TF=
P growth in the last good decades, the 1950s and 1960s, and when were the i=
deas for those factors discovered?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I asked that question, to both Claude and Perplexity, and both cited: Petro=
chemicals/Plastics, Electronics / Semiconductors, Aviation, Antibiotics / M=
edical Advances, Mass Production Techniques, all of which were conceived of=
