 It=E2=80=99s as if they were frozen in amber.=C2=A0
The question isn=E2=80=99t whether good ideas have gotten harder to find, b=
ut why it got so hard to use the good ideas we already generate.=C2=A0
In one of the best talks of the conference, Eli Dourado [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/b71a4d4c-352b-4026-951e-4faeffed7d8b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] argued that ideas aren=E2=80=99=
t getting harder to find; they=E2=80=99re getting harder to use, thanks to =
the three rules put on innovation:
This is the precautionary principle ad absurdum. The Nuclear Regulatory Com=
mission (NRC) is an obvious punching bag, and one I=E2=80=99ve punched many=
 times in these pages. The challenge isn=E2=80=99t just that they make it h=
ard and expensive to license new reactors, but that they make it illegal to=
