hese make the point.=C2=A0
Which brings us back to the question: why are people building things again =
now?=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s my hypothesis:=C2=A0
Ideas have gotten more expensive not to discover, but to build, at the same=
 time that demand for premium versions of things slowed their spending. Tha=
t meant that the initial push down the cost curve never happened, which mea=
nt that ideas remained more expensive to implement, which means they never =
got to the normal part of the demand curve.=C2=A0
Now, two things are happening.=C2=A0
Technology is making old and new ideas cheaper and easier to build.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a reemergence of =E2=80=9Cpremium demand.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Ideas Need Adoption to Make an Impact
Ideas alone are not enough. They need to be techno-economically viable, bui=
ldable for a low enough cost that the market is able to adopt them. There i=
s no progress without adoption.=C2=A0
Premium demand can help technologies that have a path to market viability r=
each that point. It=E2=80=99s a bridge. It=E2=80=99s not charity, or even g=
rants. These products offer capabilities that no other products do and for =
which the government and Big Tech are willing to pay higher prices to acces=
s those capabilities.=C2=A0
Big Tech is buying nuclear power out of its own selfish interests, and the =
AI it produces may show up in TFP growth, but nuclear power won=E2=80=99t h=
ave a large direct impact on TFP while it sits behind the meter powering da=
ta centers. That will come as a result of building and manufacturing more r=
eactors and bringing them down the learning curves. Until then, it has powe=
rful, deep-pocketed, and motivated allies to help fight the costly hurdles =
in its way.=C2=A0
The same can be said for capabilities that the DoD might buy =E2=80=93 whet=
her drones or supersonic planes =E2=80=93 which will show up first in the m=
ilitary context and diffuse to consumers as companies scale up manufacturin=
g and bring down costs. NASA and the DoD were the premium demand for SpaceX=
=E2=80=99s early launch; now, the benefits can be felt by anyone who uses S=
tarlink to access the internet.=C2=A0
For a certain set of technologies, this bridge is critical. But something e=
lse is happening, too.=C2=A0
Despite the slowdown, technological progress has marched on. Compared to 19=
73, entrepreneurs have a cornucopia of lower-cost, higher-performance techn=
ologies at their disposal with which to build. AI, CRISPR, batteries, solar=
, software, launch, materials, sensors, and an ever-expanding list of input=
s continue to improve and get cheaper.=C2=A0
Atom Limbs=E2=80=99 AI prosthetic is possible, at a price the market will p=
ay, because of advances in sensors, actuators, batteries, and machine learn=
ing.=C2=A0
Longshot Space uses advanced control systems to inject gas directly behind =
the projectile as it moves down the barrel at sub-millisecond precision, a =
capability that Gerald Bull could only have dreamed of. Plus, the DoD is a =
potential early customer for Longshot=E2=80=99s hypersonic capabilities, wh=
ich would help fund the development of the ultimate mission of launching ma=
ss into space more cheaply and helping humans, and our progress, scale beyo=
nd earth.=C2=A0
Almost any 1950s or 1960s idea that=E2=80=99s being brought back to life to=
day benefits from dramatic cost and performance improvements compared to th=
e technology available at the time.=C2=A0
Perhaps what=E2=80=99s happening is that those cost declines have outrun th=
e cost increases from regulation and other countervailing forces put up ove=
r the past fifty years. More simply: it all comes down to economics. The fa=
ctors for and against progress can be boiled down to the all-in costs to tu=
rn ideas into scaled products, and whether there are enough buyers willing =
to pay more than that cost.=C2=A0
A counterpoint might be that there=E2=80=99s a lot of economic interest beh=
ind scaling Moore=E2=80=99s Law or improving crop yields, and yet, new impa=
ctful ideas in those fields are getting harder to find. My bet would be tha=
t while those particular tech trees are reaching their end, and exhibiting =
diminishing returns to researchers, new tech trees, driven by lower input c=
osts and premium demand, will take over to move progress forward. That cert=
ainly seems to be happening with GPUs.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m not an economist, but I would love to see somebody analyze this=
=2E
If my hypothesis is true, it aligns well with my belief that we=E2=80=99re =
entering a new Techno-Economic Paradigm [ https://substack.com/redirect/4de=
9256b-c51f-4bde-855a-5181eabe542c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in the Carlota Perez sense, a Techno-Industrial=
 Revolution [ https://substack.com/redirect/c666993f-ba47-4ca5-ad66-b77323e=
2c3d8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=
 and that TFP growth may re-accelerate.
What Do You Do With an Idea?
One of the joys of parenthood is that you get to read a lot of books with y=
our kids. One of my favorite books to read with Dev and Maya is Kobi Yamada=
=E2=80=99s What Do You Do With An Idea? [ https://substack.com/redirect/26d=
5a0a2-ee59-4ba8-aa49-ef7515f7c5c0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
I don=E2=80=99t want to spoil it, but after feeling a little embarrassed by=
 his idea, trying to hide it away and protect it, what the protagonist real=
izes is that what you do with an idea is=E2=80=A6 you change the world.=C2=
=A0
Ideas are the lifeblood of progress, but they only work when you can actual=
ly use them in the world. They don=E2=80=99t work tucked away in brains or =
even published in research papers.=C2=A0
Turning ideas into progress is a complicated thing, influenced by culture, =
regulation, economics, technology, and the efforts of individuals.=C2=A0
Maybe, for fifty years, turning ideas into progress has been more expensive=
 than it=E2=80=99s worth. And anyway, driven by software, GDP has continued=
 to grow apace, even if the unexplainable part of it has not.=C2=A0
Maybe there wasn=E2=80=99t the urgency to do new hard things when a combina=
tion of the old hard things, software, and capital markets kept GDP growth =
on-trend.=C2=A0
For whatever combination of reasons, that seems to be changing, and we migh=
t be finding ourselves in this beautiful place, armed with new premium dema=
nd and better technology with which to unblock a tremendous backlog of old =
ideas that previous generations have left on the shelf.=C2=A0
Instead of harder-to-find ideas, we might have an abundance of great ideas =
for those with the skill and entrepreneurial vigor to bring to life.=C2=A0
That would imply that we don=E2=80=99t necessarily need more researchers; w=
e just need more people putting the ideas the researchers come up with to w=
ork.=C2=A0
In addition to making new Einsteins [ https://substack.com/redirect/03e9b1b=
f-f689-4992-ad08-e922a4ab185c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=C2=A0 - genius researchers will always be important=
 =E2=80=93 we need to make new Vanderbilts and Fords and Wrights. Tinkerers=
 who can pluck from the pile of withered ideas and combine them in new ways=
=2E We might also need new Librarians,=20=
who can help surface those great old i=
deas, and track which technologies and costs might make them economically v=
iable after all of these years. Maybe that=E2=80=99s where AI can be most h=
elpful.=C2=A0
Of course, we need to reverse the regulatory ratchet that makes new ideas a=
nd old ones more expensive to build. We need more people working on policy =
that helps drive down the cost of implementing good ideas. The faster and l=
ess expensive it is to build, test, and iterate, the smaller the gap betwee=
n a good idea and its contribution to progress.=C2=A0
And as we start to turn more ideas into more products, I suspect that new i=
deas will become surprisingly easy to find. Just as models need new trainin=
g data to get smarter, we need to try more things to discover which questio=
ns our researchers should ask next.=C2=A0
Thanks to Claude for editing, to Eli for letting me use his slides, and to =
Jason and Heike for putting on an incredible conference.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with a Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

