26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">The paper defines id=
eas as things that lead to Total Factor Productivity (TFP) growth.</p></li>=
<li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D=
"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">TFP is the porti=
on of economic output growth that cannot be explained by increases in the q=
uantity of inputs (like labor and capital).&#160;</p></li><li style=3D"marg=
in: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: bord=
er-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">The paper then measures research =
productivity as TFP growth divided by research input.</p></li><li style=3D"=
margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: =
border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">Finally, it concludes that be=
cause this ratio is declining, ideas are getting harder to find.</p></li></=
ul><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>By defining ideas in terms of TFP growth, the =
paper essentially assumes its conclusion.</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;">The paper does provide valuable data on the relationship be=
tween research inputs and certain economic outputs over time, and it finds =
this pattern across various domains, which suggests there's something meani=
ngful happening. And the authors have forgotten more about economics than I=
&#8217;ll ever learn, so maybe I&#8217;m missing something.&#160;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;"><strong>The problem is, the paper might actually lead to the </=
strong><em><strong>wrong</strong></em><strong> conclusion: that we need to =
throw more researchers at the problem, that we just need to produce more id=
eas.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>For one thing, it might su=
ggest that now that AI is here, we&#8217;re good.</strong><span> While the =
number of </span><em>human</em><span> researchers won&#8217;t be able to sc=
ale exponentially to offset declining research productivity, maybe the numb=
er of AI researchers can. If you assume that ideas are the bottleneck, then=
 maybe you just hold out for a sufficiently intelligent model.&#160;</span>=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The question of whether AI would just solve progress =
came up multiple times at the conference.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(5=
4, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>=
The most common response was: no, </span><strong>ideas are not the bottlene=
ck</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>On the opposit=
e end of the spectrum, it might suggest that we are really and truly screwe=
d.</strong><span> Total Factor Productivity really has fallen off since the=
 1970s, and if ideas just keep getting harder to find, and ideas are what d=
rive TFP, then we might just be in for greater and greater stagnation.</spa=
n></p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-size: 1=
