nerate the same number of ideas &#8211; then we need to produce more resear=
chers to at least match the rate of decline in research productivity.&#160;=
</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That strikes me as equivalent to observi=
ng that a football team&#8217;s yards per carry is declining and deciding t=
hat they need to run the ball more to make up for it. To torture this analo=
gy a bit, it&#8217;s maybe even more equivalent to signing </span><em>more<=
/em><span> running backs, whoever&#8217;s available off waivers, and then r=
unning the ball more with </span><em>them</em><span>, instead of fixing you=
r offensive line. Worse, there are only 53 roster spots, so every new runni=
ng back you sign means cutting someone who could be doing the blocking and =
tackling!</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>We will always need new ideas. =
In this house, we subscribe to the David Deutsch </span><a href=3D"https://=
substack.com/redirect/23607a4c-3340-4d93-a274-28785b743ef6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Principle of Optimism</a><span>:=
 &#8220;All evils are caused by insufficient knowledge.&#8221;&#160;</span>=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">And to be fair, the paper isn&#8217;t trying to sugge=
st that a lack of ideas is solely responsible for the slowdown in TFP growt=
h. It&#8217;s simply arguing that the assumption of constant research produ=
ctivity doesn&#8217;t hold up, and it makes its point.&#160;</p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">But the simplistic takeaways &#8211; that ideas are getting harder t=
