decoration: underline;">Julia DeWahl</a><span> called this demand &#8211; f=
rom both Big Tech and the DoD &#8211; &#8220;premium power.&#8221; In other=
 words, these buyers are willing to buy power more expensive than they coul=
d get from other sources in exchange for capabilities that only nuclear can=
 provide. In Big Tech&#8217;s case, that means 24/7, reliable, clean power.=
 In the DoD&#8217;s case, that means reliable power that is easy to transpo=
rt.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>This premium demand is often =
critical to the development and diffusion of technologies.</strong><span> C=
ertain buyers can support a technology when it&#8217;s more expensive than =
alternatives in the market, which provides an initial push down the cost cu=
rve. With experience, manufacturers can drive down costs to the point that =
they&#8217;re accessible to the broader market.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">As two examples, the military and NASA served as premium demand for =
both solar power and semiconductors in the late 1950s and early 1960s.&#160=
;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In 1958, Vanguard I was the first satellite to use s=
olar cells. They paid $1,000 per watt. Today, a watt of solar comes in at l=
ess than $1.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In the late 1950s and early 1960s, =
the military bought nearly all integrated circuit production for use in the=
 Minuteman missile program, and NASA&#8217;s Apollo program bought thousand=
s of integrated circuits. Then, Moore&#8217;s Law took over.&#160;</p><p st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;">Then, starting in the late 1960s, both NASA and the DoD&#8217;=
